missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:257:Vasseur's transport terms give **5/3 > 3/2** (better than CKN), but the local pressure term gives **4/3 < 3/2** (worse, in the sense of being farther from full regularity). So:
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:258:- **Where De Giorgi is better:** transport/nonlinear terms (5/3 vs 3/2)
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:259:- **Where De Giorgi hits a new wall:** local pressure (4/3 ŌĆö a new obstruction not visible in CKN)
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:264:Vasseur shows (Appendix, Conjecture 14): **if** Proposition 3 held with ╬▓_p > 3/2, then ALL suitable weak solutions would be globally bounded (full regularity). The proof rescales u_╬Ą(t,x) = ╬Ą╬╗u(tŌéĆ+╬╗┬▓t, xŌéĆ+╬╗x); the rescaled initial energy U_{╬Ą,0} ~ ╬Ą^{2ŌłÆ5/╬╗}┬Ę(global energy)┬Ę╬╗ ŌåÆ 0 as ╬╗ ŌåÆ 0 when 2╬▓ ŌłÆ 3 > 0 Ōåö ╬▓ > 3/2. So the threshold ╬▓ = 3/2 is **precisely the boundary between partial and full regularity** in the De Giorgi framework. The current proof achieves ╬▓ = 4/3 (limited by local pressure), which falls short.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:272:**No ╬Ą-absorption in the main iteration.** Unlike CKN (which uses Young's inequality with free ╬Ą to absorb gradient error terms from cutoffs), Vasseur's De Giorgi iteration uses **no free parameters in the core Proposition 3**. Every estimate is done with fixed universal constants. The only source of lossiness is:
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:274:1. **The 2^{Ck} geometric growth** in the cutoff cost (|Ōłć╬Ę_k| ~ 2^{3k}, |╬ö╬Ę_k| ~ 2^{6k}). These enter as the C^k factor in Proposition 3. This is absorbed into the De Giorgi lemma: even with C^k growth, convergence follows if ╬▓ > 1.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:276:2. **The exponent 4/3 from P_k^{21}** (see above). This is a fundamental loss ŌĆö the pressure cannot be written in divergence form, so the Riesz transform estimate loses a factor. No ╬Ą-absorption can recover this. It is a **hard structural bound**, not a proof-technique artifact.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:286:where ╬Ą is freely chosen to make the first term small and absorbed into the left side. This is classic ╬Ą-absorption. It introduces no fundamental loss (╬Ą is eventually chosen optimally), but it creates explicit "interaction terms" that must be controlled by the pressure estimate.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:288:**Vasseur avoids this ╬Ą-absorption entirely** for the level-set energy estimates, replacing it with the De Giorgi mechanism (Lemma 12 + superlinear recursion). However, the pressure localization still requires Calder├│n-Zygmund estimates with **fixed L^q constants** (not optimal, but existential), which is where the 4/3 exponent arises.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:294:- **Calder├│n-Zygmund (Riesz transform) in L^q:** Used for pressure decomposition (Lemma 13). Standard L^q boundedness for 1 < q < Ōł×. Not sharp constants.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:295:- **Mean value inequality for harmonic functions (Lemma 7):** Used for P_k^1 control. Classical, sharp up to constants.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:299:### Does De Giorgi Produce Tighter Estimates?
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:303:| Velocity nonlinear term | 3/2 (Sobolev L┬│ŌåÆL^{3/2}) | 5/3 (De Giorgi level sets; tighter) |
