missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:306:| ╬Ą-absorption | Yes (explicit per-step) | No (De Giorgi mechanism) |
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:309:**Conclusion:** De Giorgi produces tighter estimates for the velocity/transport terms (5/3 vs 3/2), but the pressure localization in Vasseur's approach produces a new obstruction at exponent 4/3. The proof is less lossy on the nonlinear terms but encounters a new pressure bottleneck. Both proofs reach the same conclusion (partial regularity, H┬╣(S) = 0) but via different "weakest links."
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:313:## Synthesis: CKN vs. Vasseur ŌĆö Does De Giorgi Offer a Different Path?
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:315:### What De Giorgi Changes
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:321:3. **Velocity nonlinear term:** Vasseur achieves exponent 5/3 > 3/2, which is better than CKN's critical 3/2 exponent. The De Giorgi level-set mechanism "beats" the natural NS scaling for the velocity term.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:325:### What De Giorgi Preserves (Same Bottleneck)
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:331:3. **The dimension bound Ōēż 1 arises through the same route:** Global energy bound Ōł½Ōł½|Ōłću|┬▓ < Ōł× ŌåÆ Vitali cover ŌåÆ ╬Ż r_i Ōēż C||Ōłću||┬▓_{L┬▓} ŌåÆ H┬╣(S) = 0. The De Giorgi iteration is used to establish the epsilon-regularity criterion; once established, the covering argument is identical to CKN.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:333:4. **Full regularity is not achieved:** Both proofs face an exponent barrier. In CKN, it is the natural NS scaling (3/2 exponent for the nonlinear term). In Vasseur, the barrier is at exponent 4/3 from the local pressure term ŌĆö actually a *harder* obstruction (lower exponent), though still > 1.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:337:Vasseur's proof does NOT offer a new route around the dimension Ōēż 1 bottleneck. The De Giorgi mechanism achieves superlinear feedback (╬▓ > 1) via a different algebraic route, but the covering argument reduces to the same inequality ╬Ż r_i Ōēż CŌł½|Ōłću|┬▓ that CKN uses. The dimension bound is not a consequence of the particular proof technique; it is a consequence of the global energy bound and the ╬Ą-regularity structure ŌĆö which are shared by all three proofs.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:339:**What Vasseur's proof does offer** is a structural identification of the obstruction to full regularity: the local pressure term P_k^{21} gives exponent 4/3, and Vasseur proves (Appendix) that ╬▓ > 3/2 would imply full regularity. So Vasseur's framework converts the question "can we prove full regularity?" into "can we control the local pressure term with exponent > 3/2?" ŌĆö a more precise formulation than CKN provides.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:345:1. **Exact form of P_k^{22}, P_k^{23} decomposition:** The three-way split of the local pressure is described in general terms by Vasseur; extracting the exact exponents (5/3 for P_k^{22,23}) requires working through Lemmas 9-10 in detail, which are only summarized here.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/vasseur-2007-proof-architecture.md:349:3. **Whether any subsequent work has improved the exponent 4/3 for the local pressure:** A search of post-2007 literature found Caffarelli-Vasseur (2010, SQG equation, different PDE) and Tran-Yu (2014, Galilean invariance argument) but did not fully verify whether Tran-Yu's approach achieves ╬▓ > 3/2 for NS itself.
missions/navier-stokes/library-inbox/lin-1998-proof-architecture.md:135:(a) **Pressure decomposition:** CKN's explicit cutoff-function approach requires decomposing p = p_1 + p_2 (Riesz-transform part + harmonic part) and estimating each piece explicitly. Lin's compactness argument absorbs this decomposition into the "the limit is well-defined" step ŌĆö the pressure control is needed to ensure compactness, but it appears as a background condition (p Ōłł L^{3/2}) rather than an explicit estimate.
