missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:4:Extract five structural features from Vasseur's 2007 De Giorgi proof of partial regularity for Navier-Stokes and compare with CKN (1982).
missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:14:Vasseur's Theorem 1 states: if sup_t Ōł½_{B(1)} |u|┬▓ + Ōł½Ōł½|Ōłću|┬▓ + ||P||_{L^p(L┬╣)}^2 Ōēż C*, then u is bounded on the inner half-cylinder. This is stated at **fixed scale** on a unit cylinder ŌĆö not in CKN's "for all r ŌåÆ 0" form. The CKN criterion E(u,r) < ╬┤* is recovered as Theorem 2 via standard NS parabolic rescaling; Vasseur claims no novelty there. The pressure condition is weaker than CKN: P Ōłł L^p(L┬╣) for any p > 1 (vs. CKN's P Ōłł L^{3/2}).
missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:20:The core novelty. Vasseur defines decreasing cylinders Q_k ŌåÆ Q_Ōł× = [ŌłÆ1/2,1]├ŚB(1/2) with increasing levels C_k = 1ŌłÆ2^{ŌłÆk} ŌåÆ 1, tracking the level-set energy U_k = sup_t Ōł½|v_k|┬▓ + Ōł½Ōł½ d_k┬▓ where v_k = [|u|ŌłÆC_k]ŌéŖ. The master inequality (Lemma 11 + Eq. 13) gives U_k Ōēż C^k┬Ę(1+||P||_{L^p(L┬╣)})┬ĘU_{kŌłÆ1}^{╬▓_p} with ╬▓_p > 1. The key departure from CKN: the pressure is decomposed into a harmonic (non-local) part P_k^1 controlled by the single global norm ||P||_{L^p(L┬╣)}, plus a local part P_k^2 depending only on u inside B_{kŌłÆ1}. This avoids the need for P Ōłł L^{3/2}(Q_r) at every scale r ŌåÆ 0.
missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:23:Parabolic Sobolev: L┬▓ energy ŌåÆ L^{10/3} (the critical exponent 2┬Ę5/3 for parabolic dimension 5 = 3+2). De Giorgi level sets give U_{kŌłÆ1}^{5/3} for transport/velocity terms (better than CKN's 3/2). But the local pressure term P_k^{21} yields exponent ╬▓ ŌåÆ 4/3 (as q ŌåÆ Ōł×). Summary: velocity terms ╬▓ = 5/3 > 3/2 (De Giorgi beats CKN here); pressure ╬▓ = 4/3 < 3/2 (new bottleneck). Net: ╬▓_p > 1 for all p > 1 ŌåÆ partial regularity; ╬▓_p < 3/2 in general ŌåÆ full regularity not achieved. Vasseur shows in an Appendix that ╬▓ > 3/2 would imply **full regularity** ŌĆö so the threshold 3/2 is precise.
missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:26:No per-step ╬Ą-absorption in the De Giorgi iteration (unlike CKN). The only free parameter is ╬╗ (chosen once in Proposition 5 to make a linear coefficient < 1/8). Lossiness is fixed by: geometric factors 2^{Ck} from cutoffs (absorbed into C^k in Lemma 4) and the hard exponent 4/3 from the local pressure term ŌĆö not a proof artifact, but a structural obstruction. De Giorgi is strictly less lossy on the velocity side (5/3 vs 3/2 for transport terms) but encounters a new pressure bottleneck.
missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:29:Vasseur's De Giorgi proof arrives at dimension Ōēż 1 via the **same Vitali covering applied to the same ╬Ą-regularity criterion** as CKN. The De Giorgi mechanism is used only to establish the ╬Ą-regularity threshold; once established, the dimension bound follows the CKN route. The structural bottleneck (H┬╣(S) = 0 but not H^╬▒(S) = 0 for ╬▒ < 1) is not a consequence of proof technique ŌĆö it reflects the global energy bound and parabolic scaling, shared by all approaches. Vasseur's value-add is a sharper identification of the full-regularity obstruction: the local pressure term contributes exponent 4/3 < 3/2, and 3/2 is precisely the threshold for full regularity.
missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:32:- **Tran-Yu (2014, AIHP):** Claims to use De Giorgi + Galilean invariance to remove the "bad scaling" local pressure term. If successful, this might achieve ╬▓ > 3/2. Worth verifying.
missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT-SUMMARY.md:38:- The De Giorgi approach actually produces a *worse* pressure exponent (4/3 < 3/2) than CKN's direct pressure estimate, even though it requires only the weaker pressure condition P Ōłł L^p(L┬╣). This means the "weaker assumptions ŌåÆ same conclusion" improvement comes at the cost of a harder internal obstruction.
