missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:166:  This works because the harmonic function P_k^1 is controlled by boundary values, which are bounded using the L┬╣ spatial norm of the full P.
missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:168:- **P_k^2 is local:** ŌłÆ╬öP_k^2 = Ōłé_iŌłé_j[Žå_k u_i u_j] on R┬│. This depends only on u inside B_{kŌłÆ1}. The local pressure is further decomposed into three pieces P_k^{21}, P_k^{22}, P_k^{23} based on splitting u = u┬Ę(1 ŌłÆ v_k/|u|) + u┬Ęv_k/|u|, where the first factor is bounded by 1 (since |u|┬Ę(1ŌłÆv_k/|u|) Ōēż C_k Ōēż 1) and the second depends on the level-set energy.
missions/navier-stokes/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-003/REPORT.md:170:**Why this works at fixed scale but not at shrinking scale:** The key insight is that ||P||_{L^p(L┬╣)} is a *single global number* that doesn't scale with k. In CKN, you would need ||P||_{L^{3/2}(Q_{r_k})} at each level r_k ŌåÆ 0, which requires the full pressure integrability. Here, the single global norm suffices because Q_k ŌåÆ Q_Ōł× ŌēĀ 0.
