missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:34:### Caffarelli-Vasseur (2010) ŌĆö "The De Giorgi method for regularity of solutions of elliptic equations and its applications to fluid dynamics"
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:36:- **Key result:** Survey paper applying De Giorgi to SQG (global regularity proved) and NS. SQG has no pressure term; the De Giorgi iteration reaches criticality (analogous to ╬▓ ŌåÆ 1 in the recursion, sufficient for L^Ōł×). This is the "control case" for the mission: without pressure, the iteration closes at the optimal exponent.
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:38:- **Relevance:** Key comparison point for Step 1 of the chain: SQG succeeds (no pressure), NS fails (pressure term hits 4/3 barrier). The exact term-by-term comparison is available from Vasseur 2007 above.
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:44:- **Key result:** Estimates on higher derivatives of NS solutions up to potential blow-up time using De Giorgi with Hardy spaces and maximal functions.
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:45:- **H^1/Hardy role:** Second derivatives of pressure lie in Hardy H^1 ŌŖé L^1 (CLMS). Explicitly acknowledges that the maximal function is not L^1-bounded, forcing a new pressure splitting strategy.
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:46:- **Relevance:** First explicit documentation of the H^1 maximal operator obstruction in the De Giorgi NS context.
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:54:- **Pressure decomposition (Lemma 3.3) ŌĆö the most sophisticated H^1-pressure + De Giorgi work to date:**
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:56:  - P_3 (k-independent non-local part): absorbed into level-set functional E_k via algebraic identity (47): div(uP_3) + (v_k/|u| ŌłÆ 1)u┬ĘŌłćP_3 = (v_k/|u|)u┬ĘŌłćP_3 Ōēź 0. This removes P_3 from the De Giorgi inequality entirely.
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:59:  - **The second derivatives of pressure lie in H^1 via CLMS**, explicitly stated on page 5. The new decomposition is designed specifically to work with H^1 pressure structure despite the non-bounded maximal operator.
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:61:- **Relevance to mission:** This paper IS the most advanced H^1 + De Giorgi work for NS pressure. It documents that the H^1 structure is already exploited in the Vasseur pressure decomposition, and it achieves ~4/3 (not 3/2).
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:68:- **Pressure strategy:** The local De Giorgi analysis is performed on the **vorticity equation** (Žē = curl u), which has no pressure term. This CIRCUMVENTS the pressure problem entirely rather than solving it.
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:69:- **Relevance:** Suggests that the Vasseur school has moved away from the H^1 pressure route (toward vorticity), which implicitly suggests the H^1 pressure route has hit a ceiling. However, this does NOT close the 4/3 ŌåÆ 3/2 gap for the full regularity conjecture.
