missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:114:### (B) H^1 + De Giorgi already tried and failure documented
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:117:The H^1/Hardy space structure of the pressure IS already exploited extensively by the Vasseur school:
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:120:- Choi-Vasseur 2014: most advanced treatment ŌĆö new pressure decomposition designed specifically to work with H^1 pressure via three-way split
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:122:**What has been tried:** Using the H^1 structure of Ōłć┬▓p (the CLMS fact) to build a pressure decomposition that controls the De Giorgi iteration. The best known result (Choi-Vasseur 2014) achieves the scaling-optimal exponent 4/3 (Ōēł 7/6) but cannot reach 3/2.
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:124:**The documented obstruction:** H^1 does not have a bounded maximal operator. This prevents direct application of standard L^p maximal function estimates in the De Giorgi scheme, requiring the elaborate three-way pressure decomposition.
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:126:**What has NOT been tried (the mission's specific angle):** The Step 2B of the chain asks whether **De Giorgi test functions Žł_k are uniformly BMO-bounded**, which would allow using the H^1-BMO duality pairing Ōł½ fg Ōēż ŌĆ¢fŌĆ¢_{H^1}┬ĘŌĆ¢gŌĆ¢_{BMO} instead of the standard H├Člder inequality. This specific route ŌĆö replacing H├Člder with H^1-BMO duality ŌĆö does **not appear in any Vasseur paper**. The Choi-Vasseur approach uses Hardy spaces and maximal functions but does not use H^1-BMO duality with the De Giorgi test functions as BMO elements.
missions/vasseur-pressure/steps/step-001/explorations/exploration-001/REPORT.md:135:No sharpness result or lower bound has been proved showing that no decomposition strategy can exceed 4/3 in the De Giorgi NS recursion. The Vasseur school's movement to vorticity (Vasseur-Yang 2021) bypassed the pressure decomposition question rather than proving it sharp.
